
compute: it is on-demand, virtualized processing power (CPU), memory (RAM), and storage provided over the internet, provided by various cloud service providers (AWS, Azure, GCP).  

EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)
Think of EC2 as renting a computer in the cloud. You can choose its size, OS, and power, and pay only for the time you use it — like renting a hotel room instead of buying a house.

Lambda
Lambda lets you run code without managing any server at all. You upload your function, and AWS runs it automatically whenever triggered (e.g., a button click or file upload). You're billed only for the milliseconds your code actually runs.

Auto Scaling
Auto Scaling automatically adds or removes EC2 servers based on traffic. If your app gets a sudden spike in users, it spins up more servers; when traffic drops, it shuts them down — saving cost and keeping performance smooth.   

Elastic Beanstalk
Beanstalk is like a smart helper that handles deployment for you. You upload your app code, and AWS automatically sets up the servers, load balancers, and scaling — ideal for developers who don't want to manage infrastructure manually.  
